{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"255fba13-f2dc-4efa-8240-93a5997dfffd","content":"Here's how to migrate your Azure DevOps pipeline from **VSTest@3** to **Microsoft.Testing.Platform**:\n\n### 1. Replace `VSTest@3` with `dotnet test`\n\n```yaml\n# Before (VSTest@3)\n- task: VSTest@3\n  inputs:\n    testAssemblyVer2: '**/*Tests.dll'\n    resultsFolder: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults'\n    codeCoverageEnabled: true\n\n# After (Microsoft.Testing.Platform via dotnet test)\n- task: DotNetCoreCLI@2\n  displayName: 'Run tests'\n  inputs:\n    command: 'test'\n    projects: '**/*Tests.csproj'\n    arguments: >-\n      --configuration $(BuildConfiguration)\n      --logger \"trx;LogFileName=testresults.trx\"\n      --results-directory $(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults\n      --collect \"Code Coverage\"\n```\n\n### 2. Update your test project\n\nAdd these NuGet packages to each test `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<ItemGroup>\n  <PackageReference Include=\"MSTest\" Version=\"3.7.0\" />\n  <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.6.2\" />\n  <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage\" Version=\"17.13.2\" />\n</ItemGroup>\n\n<!-- Enable the new platform runner -->\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n  <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### 3. Publish results & coverage\n\n```yaml\n- task: PublishTestResults@2\n  displayName: 'Publish test results'\n  condition: always()\n  inputs:\n    testResultsFormat: 'VSTest'\n    testResultsFiles: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults/**/*.trx'\n\n- task: PublishCodeCoverageResults@2\n  displayName: 'Publish code coverage'\n  condition: always()\n  inputs:\n    summaryFileLocation: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults/**/*.cobertura.xml'\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n- **`EnableMSTestRunner`** makes each test project a standalone executable using Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n- **`TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport`** ensures `dotnet test` can still orchestrate the new runner.\n- Use `condition: always()` on publish steps so results appear even on test failures.\n- The TRX logger and code coverage collector are now opt-in NuGet packages rather than built-in VSTest features.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"70056461-18c1-4308-b64e-df7de6b6fafe","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory seems empty. This is a general question about migrating from VSTest@3 to Microsoft.Testing.Platform in Azure DevOps CI pipelines. Let me provide guidance based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":721,"requestId":"4C24:1414DF:D7D25D:10C0001:6A0129E5"},"id":"4470bb33-3919-45af-850e-9511ff0f52a6","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:59:29.459Z","parentId":"a773584c-78c9-45d3-8722-14e846b5f9d2"}
